Thank you OCAD University and Professor Alexander Manu for such an incredible conversation. 

We dove head first into the future of creativity in a world with artificial intelligence and the Metaverse. We discussed how Ai doesn’t mean knowledge is being taken away, but instead knowledge is being changed. 

We shed light on why today’s vision of the Metaverse is missing the mark. And what could be possible if we get it right.

We debated the ethics of Ai creations. The future of work.  Crypto. NFTs and the currencies of the future. And much more.

We will be sharing all the footage on social media over the next few weeks. 

I’m so grateful that this is what I get to call work.
A lot more to come. Stay tuned! 🤖

Shedding light on our future with technology—and hopefully bringing new voices to the table—brings me so much joy.

The thing about the future is we can’t predict it. No one can. But the more we know about the technologies around us the better equipped we are to lean towards and shape the futures that we want to be a part of.

It’s pretty surreal to be living through this scientific breakthrough. We are at the birth of a new energy source. One that is clean, unlimited and cheap. We are likely a few decades away from commercializing this technology, but we have taken a big step towards it. 

Nuclear fusion is the same energy that powers the sun. Two hydrogen atoms are fused together to create helium and excess energy. 
Scientists have tried to recreate this reaction for decades but have failed. Until now. 

Scientists achieved this breakthrough by pointing hundreds of lasers at a fraction of a second at two hydrogen atoms. Fusing them together to create helium and excess energy. 

Nuclear energy would be cleaner and more reliable than renewables such as wind and solar. And much cheaper.

One step closer to a carbon-free unlimited energy future.

I got the chance to chat with @breakfasttelevision on the complicated ethics of avatars. In particular, the opportunity this technology presents to exploit marginalized identities. 

Technology will allow us to present our humanity to the world in new ways. And there are many reasons why showing up NOT as your exact physical self will be freeing and liberating. We can take on new roles with this technology and that will be a beautiful thing. 

But what concerns me is the potential for misrepresentation and exploitation of communities for profit. For example, a non-Black dj who uses a Black avatar during Black history month and books a bunch of culturally significant digital events as a result. Or a company that doesn’t have one person of color on the payroll, but has created a series of diverse avatars for customer facing roles like customer service or brand ambassadors. Situations like these are where my ethical alarm bells go off and why the human identities behind avatars matter.

It’s a very exciting time in technology. And I think Avatars are going to open up incredible avenues of creativity and self expression. But as with any technology, there are important ethical conversations that need to accompany it.

Today is #WorldDayofSocialJustice. It was created by the United Nations in 2007 to call attention to the vast social injustices and challenges we face across the globe, and to center and strategize solutions that can advance the social justice agenda forward.

At the moment we face great economic and social crises across the world. Many of the least developed countries are in the midst of a severe food crisis caused by surging food prices as a result of the war. There is an ongoing climate crisis leaving millions displaced. And as we heard from @antoniabask today, 80% of people who are displaced from climate change are women. There are vast inequities when it comes to access to fair and decent jobs. Along with enormous (and widening) gaps in wealth distribution.
Geopolitical tensions are fracturing pathways to progress. And most recently, there is severe devastation and destabilization in Turkey and Syria as a result of the heartbreaking earthquake only weeks ago. All of this coming off the heals of the COVID-19 pandemic.

I got the opportunity to hear from incredibly inspiring young leaders from around the world who have been mobilizing, organizing and strategizing towards a new social agenda. From equipping their local communities with the skills needed to thrive in the digital future; to implementing an intersectional lens for national and international policies; to calls and ideas for a more equitable global financial system. And a shared passion for the exciting role that technology and entrepreneurship can play by creating new pathways for economic security, education and digital inclusion. 

The pathway to progress is certainly uphill, but there is no shortage of leaders!

Thank you to The Permanent Mission of the Kyrgyz Republic to the UN, the ILO, the @ituofficial the UNCTAD and the UN Department of Economic and Social Affairs for convening the commemorative meeting of the 2023 World Day of Social Justice. And thank you so much for the opportunity to share my remarks on behalf of the bright young voices we heard in the morning Youth Dialogue and the Generation Connect Visionaries Board. 🇺🇳

What should we do about AI and education?

It was great joining @cnnthismorning to discuss the impact of AI on education and on society more broadly. 

We talked about a recent story where an "AI detection tool" incorrectly flagged a student's essay as "AI generated."

The purpose of education is to prepare students for the world of tomorrow. That world will include AI so we need to figure out how to incorporate it into curriculums instead of banning it.

I was so honored to moderate yesterday’s roundtable discussion at the @unitednations on Generative AI. With representatives from Microsoft, Google, the World Bank, the Permanent Representative of Romani, among others. 

Clearly we are at a pretty critical moment in history as it relates to technological innovation. 

Artificial intelligence presents numerous opportunities for society. But also creates significant risks and challenges if we don’t steer it intentionally. 

Ensuring AI works for the common good won’t happen automatically. It requires an “all hands on deck” approach. 

We also can’t just center the voices of tech leaders. We need representatives from non-profits, civil society and community groups which provide invaluable insight into areas such fairness, representation and safety. 

If we want to steer AI in the right direction, we will have to come back to the table time and time again to make sure this technology works for all. 

Thank you to the Broadband Commission for Sustainable Development for convening this dialogue.

I haven’t really shared my full *career story*.. So here it is!  @fashionography 🎥🎥 (And a little bit more of my personality☺️)

I grew up chasing other people’s versions of success. I never stopped to define it for myself. And when I arrived at the life I thought I wanted, I realized this was not at all the person who I wanted to be. So I took a chance and decided to pave a new path for myself. 

Here’s what I’ve learned:
- focus less on *what* you want to do and more on *who* you want to be. 
 -fear is usually the the map pointing you in the direction you should be going
- there is no *ideal moment* to pick up and change your life.. you will always be pressing go before you feel ready. At some point you’re going to have to take a leap of faith. But that’s ok because life doesn’t wait, either:)
- you have the right to rewrite your resume. We grow and change over time, personally and professionally.
- we are more than one thing

Hi from Geneva at the @unitednations AI for Good Summit 🇺🇳🇺🇳🇺🇳🇺🇳🇺🇳

Where are we in this moment? 

An important question we need to ask ourselves when it comes to our future with artificial intelligence. A technology that the world will largely be built on top of. It could take us to new heights in healthcare, education, science and discovery. It may prove to be humanity’s best inventor. 

But unfortunately safety is not the default setting with this technology. And despite a country’s best efforts, AI is largely borderless. Which means global collaboration on the limits we want to place on this technology is essential. We also need to ensure that it’s not just those who are building AI who get to decide how we regulate and safeguard it. Something I’m quite concerned about based on the events of the past few months.

As global organizations that transcend national boundaries, this is a really important moment for the @unitednations and @ituofficial . I’m grateful for the critical role they are playing in stewarding cross-border conversations and initiatives, while also recognizing the sense of urgency of this moment. 

What became ever so apparent at the UN #AIforGood summit this past week are the brilliant minds all across the world who are coming together to ensure that humanity stands to benefit from this transformational technology.
An extraordinary thing to witness. 

Until next time, Geneva 🇨🇭 🇺🇳

Announcement📣 🗣️🗣️🗣️: I am finally stepping into the world of YouTube! 
As someone who studies the future for a living, I want to invite you into this world with me!

We all deserve to be invited to the conversations about OUR own futures. We all deserve to have a say in the ways technologies are shaping our world. It shouldn’t just be up to what feels like five or six people in Silicon Valley. But it starts with equipping ourselves with the information we need to insert ourselves in the conversations we want to be a part of.

I am going to bring you explainers, interviews, my take on things. The ethical challenges of emerging technologies. The inspiring ways technologies are changing our world. I’ll share some of my talks on this channel. And I would love to hear from you the areas and topics you want me to cover. The people you think I should interview. All of it.

The future isn’t just about what happens tomorrow. It’s about the decisions that we make today that shape tomorrow. The more we understand the technologies around us the better equipped we are to steer the future in directions we want it to go. 

Regardless of what you believe to be true about the future, the best thing we can do is prepare for it.

See you on YouTube < you can subscribe via the link in bio>. Thanks for your support on this new journey🥳

While data can help guide strategic forecasting and scenario planning, no one (not even futurists) can predict the future (at least according to current science theories ;) ). But that doesn’t mean we shouldn’t prepare for the different possible outcomes of the technology. Preparation allows us to move towards the futures that we want and away from the futures we don’t want. The more you learn about the future the better you can shape it.

Zoom has been coming under fire for recent changes to their data policies that involve using data from our meetings to train AI systems. We been here before in the social media age: exploiting data for free in exchange services doesn’t end up well.

Of course we need large healthy data sets to build AI. But we have to move towards better business models to acquire that data. Or new ways to generate the data entirely.

First YouTube episode is live🥳! On a topic I promised I would dive into 2+ months ago.

We’ve all seen the headlines: writers and actors are striking, streaming has majorly disadvantaged creators and AI is transforming Hollywood.

A few months ago I promised I would do a full YouTube video on the future of AI in Hollywood, and how the writers, actors and the creatives who make Hollywood what it is can shape how the technology evolves. So here it is! 

While technological evolution is inevitable in Hollywood as it is in any other industry. The actual path it takes isn’t. We can shape that. But it requires us to learn about the future so we can actively move towards the futures that we want and pivot away from the futures that we don’t want.

In this episode I cover the future of screenwriting, the future of acting, and the future of ethics in Hollywood. I share a few hot takes throughout the episode, including one about Hollywood studios. Who up until this point have largely had the upper hand… 

<Link in bio!>

Digital twins in Hollywood present unique ethical challenges. For instance, they create an opportunities to bring back deceased actors or more easily render actors in films. But as a result, we may just cycle through the same characters without making space for new talent. 

But AI also presents opportunities for new creative voices to come on the scene. Such as indie creators who would never have been seen by a big studio. Or creators who use AI to generate new types of films and content all together. 

As I state in the episode, digital twins may be something viewers and actors decide we don’t want. Which is all the more reason to think through the different ways AI could be used in the future, so we can make better decisions in the present and ensure more voices get to shape how the industry evolves. Not just those with outsized resources.

Some of the biggest media companies including CNN, Disney, NYT, Vox, ESPN, Amazon and many others are now blocking OpenAI’s web crawler from scraping the data from their websites. (Banks and financial institutions too).

This doesn’t remove the data that has already been scraped. And so you might think, what’s the point of blocking the bot now?

Here’s why this move is actually important 💡

If we’ve reached this point then it’s a pretty incredible time for science.

The driving force behind synthetic embryo research is to gain better visibility into those early days of embryo development. Which is often where miscarriages occur.

I explain more in this video, and where things could go in the future.

As always my intention is to raise public awareness on these topics so more people get a chance to weigh in on how the science and corresponding ethical guardrails evolve. 

I’ll definitely be writing/ sharing more on this topic.

I had the honor of interviewing my friend, a fellow sister and one of the most important voices in AI, @poetofcode on her new book Unmasking AI. 

Joy’s work is a reminder that there are leading voices across the world dedicating their lives to building technology on the right side of history. There are voices such as Joy’s reminding us that we have a choice in the futures we choose to create. 

An excerpt from Unmasking AI:

“ I challenge us to do much better as a society when it comes to the AI tools we create. Our standards need to exceed, not just match, the status quo, which serves only to perpetuate inequality. Most important, we need to be able to recognize that not building a tool or not collecting intrusive data is an option, and one that should be the first consideration. Do we need this Ai system or this data in the first place, or does it allow us to direct money at inadequate technical Band-Aids without addressing much larger systemic societal issues?”

Onward my friend. We are following.

We often think of climate change in terms of sea levels rising, CO2 emissions and increasing temperatures..but this is not where the story ends. Climate change, a threat multiplier, exacerbates vulnerabilities and deepens inequalities. Including violence against women and girls. 

I am deeply honored to have hosted the @unitednations @spotlightinitiative conversation at COP28, focusing on the critical yet underrepresented issue of the intersection between climate change and gender-based violence. This event brought together esteemed leaders including UNODC Executive Director Ghada Waly and UN Women Deputy Executive Director Sarah Hendriks, along with a diverse panel of social epidemiologists, activists, and land defenders. Their insights shed light on the vital importance of amplifying community leaders' voices in our dialogues. We delved into the necessity of integrating gender-based violence awareness into our climate activism and underscored the imperative of incorporating the intersectional impacts of climate change into policy and regulation. Such discussions are pivotal in driving meaningful change and ensuring a more inclusive, just and resilient future.

Ensuring technology serves every community begins with equal and fair access to education, tools, and the pivotal conversations that shape its trajectory.

2024 is one of the most significant election years in history. 

Over 50 elections impacting over 4 billion people. Including presidential elections in US and Taiwan and a general election in India. 

We need to be extra careful about how AI and social engineering could play a role in our information ecosystems (deepfakes, misinformation, disinformation by adversarial countries, fear-mongering strategies by candidates). But we may also be confronted by a new challenge: a situation where real footage emerges of a candidate doing something damaging but the candidate claims it was AI-generated. Sowing more confusion and distrust in truth by the mere suggestion of AI. I call this the AI moment of truth. The moment we start questioning the undeniable truth. 

We need to think extra critically about the information we come across online. Check sources. Verify with news rooms, etc.,
